[{"id":"VR252081","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"direction_paragraph\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">Show all your work. Indicate clearly the methods you use, because you will be scored on the correctness of your methods as well as on the accuracy and completeness of your results and explanations.</p>\n&nbsp;\n\n<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\">A researcher will conduct a study to investigate whether a new medicated skin cream is effective in curing a common skin ailment.</p>\n\n<p class=\"passage_para\">The researcher will use one of the following designs for the study.</p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li class=\"list_paragraph\"><span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Method</span> <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext mathvariant=\"bold\">I</mtext></math></span></span>: Obtain <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"320\"><math alttext=\"320\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>320</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> volunteers from the population of people with the skin ailment. Randomly assign <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"120\"><math alttext=\"120\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>120</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> people to a group to use the medicated skin cream each day. Randomly assign <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"200\"><math alttext=\"200\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>200</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> people to a group to use a placebo each day. Observe the number of people cured in each group after six months.</li>\n\t<li class=\"list_paragraph\"><span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Method</span> <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext mathvariant=\"bold\">II</mtext></math></span></span>: Randomly select <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"320\"><math alttext=\"320\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>320</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> people from the population of people with the skin ailment to use the medicated skin cream each day. Observe the number of people cured after six months.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"item_part part_id:a part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"a\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(a) If the researcher were to choose Method <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>II</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, describe, in the context of the study, a statistical reason for using <span class=\"formatted_text text_decoration:underline\">stratified</span> random sampling instead of simple random sampling in this design.</p>\n</div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252081_rubric"},{"id":"VR252081","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:b part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"b\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(b) The researcher is considering using an alternate design: a matched-pairs design. Explain a benefit that a matched-pairs design would bring to the investigation and identify a characteristic that can be used to group the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"320\"><math alttext=\"320\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>320</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> people into pairs.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252081_rubric"},{"id":"VR252081","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:c part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"c\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The researcher conducted the study using the design described in Method <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>I</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. The results of the study are shown in the following bar graph.</p>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a bar graph. The vertical axis is labeled “Frequency,” and the numbers 0 through 140, in increments of 20, are indicated. The following two categories are indicated on the horizontal axis: Medicated Skin Cream and Placebo. Each category has two bars. A key indicates that one bar represents Cured, and that the other bar represents Not cured. The data are as follows. Medicated Skin Cream. Cured, 88. Not cured, 32. Placebo. Cured, 119. Not cured, 81.\" height=\"294\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR252081.g01.png\" width=\"400\" /></div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(c) Suppose one person is randomly selected from each group (Medicated Skin Cream and Placebo) in the study. A student claims that the likelihood of selecting a person cured of the common skin ailment is <span class=\"formatted_text text_decoration:underline\">less</span> for the Medicated Skin Cream group than for the Placebo group because the total number cured in the study is <span class=\"formatted_text text_decoration:underline\">less</span> for the Medicated Skin Cream group than for the Placebo group. Explain the error in the student’s claim.</p>\n</div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252081_rubric"},{"id":"VR252081","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:d part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"d\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The researcher will use the sample data to complete a hypothesis test to investigate the following research question.</p>\n\n<div class=\"table_wrapper\">\n<table class=\"tgroup cols:1 colsep:0 rowsep:0\">\n\t<colgroup>\n\t\t<col class=\"colspec align:center colname:col1 colnum:1 colwidth:350\" />\n\t</colgroup>\n\t<tbody class=\"tbody\">\n\t\t<tr class=\"row\">\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col1\">Is there a difference between use of the new medicated skin cream and use of the placebo in the curing of the common skin ailment?</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t</tbody>\n</table>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Let <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"p sub M\"><math alttext=\"p sub M\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><mrow><mtext>M</mtext></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> be the proportion of people similar to those in the study who would be cured using the medicated skin cream, and let <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"p sub P\"><math alttext=\"p sub P\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><mrow><mtext>P</mtext></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> be the proportion of people similar to those in the study who would be cured using a placebo. The hypotheses of the test used by the researcher are as follows.</p>\n\n<p class=\"text-center\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"H sub 0: p sub M equals p sub P. H sub a: p sub M is not equal to p sub P.\"><math alttext=\"H sub 0: p sub M equals p sub P. H sub a: p sub M is not equal to p sub P.\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mo>{</mo><mtable columnalign=\"left\" width=\"auto\"><mtr><mtd><msub><mrow><mtext>H</mtext></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><mo>:</mo><msub><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><mrow><mtext>M</mtext></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><mrow><mtext>P</mtext></mrow></msub></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><msub><mrow><mtext>H</mtext></mrow><mrow><mtext>a</mtext></mrow></msub><mo>:</mo><msub><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><mrow><mtext>M</mtext></mrow></msub><mo>≠</mo><msub><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><mrow><mtext>P</mtext></mrow></msub></mtd></mtr></mtable></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span></p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(d) Describe, in the context of the study, a consequence of making a Type <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>II</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> error.</p>\n</div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252081_rubric"},{"id":"VR252081","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:e part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"e\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The conditions for inference have been met. A <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"95%\"><math alttext=\"95%\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>95</mn><mo>%</mo></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> confidence interval to estimate <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"p sub M minus p sub P\"><math alttext=\"p sub M minus p sub P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><mrow><mtext>M</mtext></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><msub><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><mrow><mtext>P</mtext></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"0.03 comma 0.24\"><math alttext=\"0.03 comma 0.24\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mn>0.03</mn></mrow><mo>,</mo><mrow><mn>0.24</mn></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>.</p><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(e) Based on the confidence interval, how should the researcher answer the research question? Explain your answer.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252081_rubric"}]